segments.text: Well, first of all, what's your name?
And where in Mexico were you born?
On one side of Salamanca, on the coast of Salamanca.
In a ranch, just over there.
It's like everybody said, the brine in here, the bottom, or something like that.
It's like here, the bottom, you know.
Is your ranch near a river?
What is the name of that river?
Now when I wanted to fix my papers for my passport,
They said that there was no record of anyone there.
Well, since I've been here for many years, since I passed my passport and settled it.
And from there, when I came from...
When I came from over there, I was in Fort Worth.
Fort Worth lasted eight days, and in eight days I walked back again.
Yeah, when I first came here.
Then just, I think it's close, but in August,
in September, I don't know, I don't remember so good, but one of those months.
Then, but, you know, last January, yes, that's when I get a lot of work, because I have no time to spend, but, you know, I was just working from 4 o'clock to work.
And then I stayed eight days, and then eight days,
on some kind of camp, make work, you see.
Y en qué año venía a los Estados Unidos en primero?
But they didn't find a record there, too.
Because I wanted some kind of record, but at that time, until 1930, I believe, that's when I wanted a record, you see.
Because she wanted a record that way, and she couldn't
I can't get nothing in Hueco, too.
Because you can't find nothing in Hueco.
But she passed a long time in my, the records that she throw away, or I don't know, because I never signed my name.
I know I couldn't sign it, because I never signed it at that time.
And where did you come across the border?
Where did you come into Texas?
No, no, you had to cross to the bridge.
Well, back before that, when you were growing up in Mexico, what was it like?
Well, a long time ago, I never seen no cars over there.
Now I've been all down there.
I see tractor in the field too.
You know, if it don't rain, there's plenty of water.
Now, she don't have it before.
There was water, but not in the river.
They didn't go up there to water the land.
What kind of work did your mother and father have?
It was just a little ranch.
Well, I never met the landowner.
There was one who gave me a piece of land.
If I had to work the land, mules or whatever, he gave me a piece of land to work.
And the other, if it didn't look good, he didn't give it to me.
Were they from this part of Mexico?
I have all my brothers, I don't think anyone came here, just me.
And I'm the only one alive because they all died.
How many brothers did you have?
I had three brothers and two sisters, but they all died.
Now it's just their nephews and their children.
And all of your nephews are in Mexico?
And during the revolution, were there problems in your ranch?
During the revolution, well, they were at home at night.
It's like here, I'm in my house.
At night they come and knock on the door, I go out to see.
And then they put the carabiners there, that I have carabiners, I have something here.
And they want to kill me because they say, and they go in to see what's there.
No, yo creo que tendría como unos 10 o 12 años.
After 1912, is everything good or are there more problems?
When the revolution ended, there were a lot of people who came to the houses.
They said it was Pancho Villa.
And no, it was Pancho Villa.
Four or five of them would go to steal from the other ranch.
They would take what they had and say, go with Pancho Villa.
Pancho Villa didn't do anything to the people.
Pancho Villa would steal from the ones who had money, not the poor ones.
because they didn't want to pay.
I remember that my father told him that he worked for three reales in Mexico at that time.
I don't think I can make a living right now.
Because I'm used to it here now.
I like seeing her go and stay awake and coming back.
Let's say we go by bus or train.
We get on the plane from San Antonio and in an hour and a half we get to Guadalajara.
And from there we take the bus to Salamanca.
What time do we get there?
Did it look like you remember, or did it look different, Mexico?
No, it's not the same as it was when I was there.
In what way was it different?
It was different because there were no cars.
They planted it the same way, but they have a different way of working.
Before that, they used to work on the land with a mill.
What kind of animals did they have these days?
There were some who collected them.
But there are no mudas these days?
We went to the ranch where I was born.
We went to the ranch and stayed there for a while and then we came back.
Viven unos allí, otros allá por retirado, y otros para allá, y así no viven, solos.
And who lived in your parents' house last April?
I didn't know them because they are other people.
But was it the same house?
Is it possible to see your book?
Your father's being kind enough to tell me something about his experiences.
trying to record stories of people who came here between 1910 and 1920.
And before he died, what kind of work did he have?
The same kind of work, to plant there.
Well, that's where I came from.
He was half a year old.
He didn't work yet, but he knew what he was doing.
They got married, but they died.
The men got married with them.
And where do your brothers-in-law live now?
They are there, in the ranch.
In the ranch, not in the city?
My sister-in-law is the wife of this one.
I turn on the light and look.
I mean, I didn't learn much.
They have so many that I don't even know.
There are two girls and two boys.
Did they also live in Salamanca?
No, I think they are in Mexico.
What kind of work did these girls have?
I don't know because I didn't know.
I didn't know when I came.
What kind of work did you have?
Well, when you were about 20 years old, you left for Texas, right?
How many days did it take?
I left, I left from there, they took me to the train.
We took the train and stopped in a part over there, in Palme Gonzales.
From there, we took another train and it came all the way here to Laredo.
There are no relatives or anyone in the United States?
Well, this is a very brave thing, isn't it?
After you came to the United States.
Well, he says he works in the Bastrog mines.
Is this your first job here?
No, because I was working on the wagon.
But from there, when I went to Anto, I worked in the mines.
And this, what is this thing?
This is where they took out the coal.
There they left something there and they emptied it down and took it up.
And for how many years do you work in Bastro?
I was already there for a year.
From there I went to Chicago in 1926.
I came and I was released again.
And when I came back, I was working there again, and I came back.
And then I didn't come back, but I came back in 1928.
On the 8th of September, I came here to the Boramo.
Here I am working, and I don't go anywhere.
I worked a lot there in the ranches.
Until I came here, to the town.
I don't remember which year it was.
And where was your husband born?
In what year did you come to the United States?
My mother had a son and we came with him.
He sent us here again with him.
My father was already dead for many years.
He wanted us to come here with him.
He was 15 years old when he passed away and we came here with him.
Here we are, we have been here for many years.
I have been to Mexico many times, but I'm just going to visit, that's all.
Because I don't live there in Mexico, it's my land and everything, I mean, I was born there.
But I'm already further away from here, and I think he too.
Yes, because now that we went there, because the ranches are very sad, he taught us where he grew up and everything.
In the village it's a little bit better.
In Salamanca it's a little bit better.
Because in the rural areas it's not.
And what part of life do you have in the ranch?
No, the ones that are in the ranch... No school?
The ones in the ranch, no.
The ones in the village, yes.
But the ones in the ranch, they go to school.
Now that we went, we didn't look.
Now that we went, we saw that in the ranch.
In the ranch, there are so many boys who go to school, but nothing.
No, in the ranch, they don't.
They grow up, they work where they can, in labor, I think.
I didn't know how to read.
I didn't know how to read when I went to this side.
I came to teach myself how to read here with my friends.
I taught myself how to make letters.
Now I can't do it anymore.
I can read a letter and... Who knows?
I didn't know how to read.
There aren't any, I think, yet.
But it's very beautiful, the place we went to.
It's been a year since April.
We went there on the 15th of April.
We went there on the 15th of April.
Next April, it will be a year.
You go there all year round?
Yes, we went there for a week.
Well, for me it's not very far, as we saw.
No, well, in the long run.
In the long run, but... Over there it's...
Yes, because people take about three days to get there.
Yes, about two and a half days.
No, I don't think it's even that far.
How do the guys from Sino-Michigan get here?
They stay here for a day, and then it's one night, and then all night, and then a whole day, and then they get here.

And then they go back, and they want to know... And then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back, and then they go back,
And in what year did you meet him?
And what kind of work did you have in Bastrop?
I did nothing at home with my mother.
How old were you at that time?
And your mother, what kind of work did she have?
I assisted people, I aborted people.
My brother is also in the mine.
And your family in Bastrak was only these three people?
We're still working on the mine.
No, we don't work there much.
They are on Iowa and other places.
From here, when we went to work in the time of the war, we were working.
Before that, did you go to other places or only after the war?
We went to work in Metaveli.
Metaveli and then to La Cebolla.
I don't remember how many years it lasted.
We lived like four years in a row.
We went, we came back and we were here like right now.
Right now there is no work over there.
In May we started to get work.
That was when we came back from here to work there again.
And then we came back again, because what we had left, I didn't have work anywhere else.
Only in the farm, in the labor.
But that was the work that we did every year.
We had to walk on the street.
We had to clean the table.
Now they say that they bring a hoe like here in the ranch.
They gave us a hoe and they would mow it for us.
In Pinaba, yes, or in Cabo.
That's how they did the work, but it was very hard.
Yes, the work was very hard.
And were you there by car or?
Sometimes we were on the train.
The first time we were on the train.
The first time we went in a truck.
There was a man who brought a truck.
The second time we went on the train.
They sent us tickets for the train.
The other time I bought a car and we went in it.
And the next year we were...
I couldn't go there anymore when one of the girls who helped me got married.
And then the other one too.
And then she wasn't as good as this one who is here.
This one, since she was a little girl, she was told that her feet weren't good.
And I didn't leave because then I had to take them to Galveston.
There were many trips from here to Galveston to help them and bring them and all that.
And where did you live during the rest of the year, during this year?
When we went and came back.
We rented a house over there.
And what kind of work did you have during the rest of the year?
No, I came here, I worked in the city, I worked where they gave me work, and I worked.
I didn't work all the time in one single job.
Different, because when I worked in the city I was digging.
So I didn't have a machine.
And when I worked with the plumber, it was the same.
And now what kind of work?
Now I'm working in the school.
No, it's good because it's not very heavy.
Well, there is the church and the Catholic school.
The big church of San Jose.
And there is also the school.
And they do the cleaning of everything.
For how many years did you have this job?
I've been there for about 4 or 5 years now.
Who knows how long you've been working there?
I've been there for about 4 or 5 years.
And all her children went to school here?
And these are more... Ah, Chiquita got married, is she her oldest daughter?
And her husband is from here?
Well, here they got married, but they left for another country.
Here they got married and they have a mother.
This lady who just came is his sister.
And what kind of work did Chinta have?
I think he worked in Piscando Algodón and all that.
They worked like that when they were here.
But since they left, they didn't...
They also went to Betabel, over there, when they left.
No, it's just that there was work there on the Antani plant and there it is.
She's working in a hospital now.
And this is your... Is this about your trip?
They took her there, I think, in Brandeis.
There are a lot of refineries there.
I don't know what they do there.
Because it was so different from where you came from.
Yes, it was so different from the years I lived there.
Was life different in the ranch as well?
The farms are not the same.
I think they are the same.
They are sown, we saw the wheat sown, like here, where there are parts that are sown in wheat, oats and chickpeas, and all that, alfalfa and everything.
The people, the people of the ranch live with what they get from work, that's all.
¿Y su familia fue de un rancho también?
There are mines here on the banks of the river.
Is the life of the mines different from the life of the ranch?
Yes, because the ranch is pure labor.
Well, in those mines, one is buried on the way, almost on the way.
It goes down, it goes about 200 feet down.
And then it walks underneath to go to work there, far from there.
And when the time comes, it comes there and they take it out.
But if it breaks, it falls.
Those who have died there, here in Mexico,
In Mexico, a mine exploded and many people died.
She was the one we went to see.
I think this is the little house.
It's going to be renovated, right?
This is the little house where I was born.
They were condemned in that little house.
There is a man on the other side and they have this thing to pass to this side.
And he threw it inside and passed it to this side.
They portrayed the man with that.
Was he the same in the days before 1920?
There was one, but that one was worn with a stick.
Well, here is where they portrayed the man who came.
This is the man who brought the gun.
He said that they portrayed him again.
When he passed by, they portrayed him again.
Is your ranch far away from Salamanca or not?
How long does it take to get there?
We would go in the morning to the village.
We would get up at 4 a.m. and we would wake up in the village.
I was afraid of crossing the river when my father died.
We had to cross that bridge and we were so far apart.
I was afraid of crossing the bridge because we were surrounded by water.
And the people who lived in your house, were they nice or not?
The people who now live here.
We just went there because... And there are people in the house, there are people living there.
We went there for my sister-in-law.
My sister-in-law was the one who took me there.
We had gone on our own, who knows if they found us.
There was a lady who said she remembered me.
She lives alone in that little house.
There she cooks, there she sleeps and everything.
It's a fireplace, there she makes food.
And he says he remembers that rabbit because he met him when he was very young.
But he is not a relative?
No, he is just a friend.
And life there is not very different.
Well, it's different here, because here you live better.
Here you live better than there.
Well, life here in Texas is better now or not?
Because before we also worked, I worked to be a father since the day.
Now, more or less, you earn more than a dollar an hour.
Everything is expensive, but you earn more.
You pay your bills, or whatever.
But at that time, everything was very cheap.
The food, the clothes, everything, everything was cheap.
But as you wish, you didn't have to pay three pesos to buy a pair of pants.
Otherwise, it would cost you one peso.
Well, you would have to pay one peso to the three of us to buy the food.
As you wish, it's very different now.
